{"ROC":[{"def":"A monstrous bird of Arabian mythology.","pos":""}],"ROCAMBOLE":[{"def":"A name of Allium Scorodoprasum and A.","pos":""}],"ROCCELLIC":[{"def":"Pertaining to, or designating, a dibasic acid of the oxalic series found in archil (Roccella tinctoria, etc.","pos":""}],"ROCCELLIN":[{"def":"A red dyestuff, used as a substitute for cochineal, archil, etc.","pos":""}],"ROCHE ALUM":[{"def":"A kind of alum occuring in small fragments; -- so called from Rocca, in Syria, whence alum is said to have been obtained; -- also called rock alum.","pos":""}],"ROCHELIME":[{"def":"Lime in the lump after it is burned; quicklime.","pos":""}],"ROCHELLE":[{"def":"A seaport town in France.","pos":""}],"ROCHET":[{"def":"A linen garment resembling the surplise, but with narrower sleeves, also without sleeves, worn by bishops, and by some other ecclesiastical dignitaries, in certain religious ceremonies.","pos":""}],"ROCHING CASK":[{"def":"A tank in which alum is crystallized from a solution.","pos":""}],"ROCK":[{"def":"A distaff used in spinning; the staff or frame about which flax is arranged, and from which the thread is drawn in spinning.","pos":""}],"ROCK SHAFT":[{"def":"A shaft that oscillates on its journals, instead of revolving, -- usually carrying levers by means of which it receives and communicates reciprocating motion, as in the valve gear of some steam engines; -- called also rocker, rocking shaft, and way shaft.","pos":""}],"ROCK STAFF":[{"def":"An oscillating bar in a machine, as the lever of the bellows of a forge.","pos":""}],"ROCKAWAY":[{"def":"Formerly, a light, low, four-wheeled carriage, with standing top, open at the sides, but having waterproof curtains which could be let down when occasion required; now, a somewhat similar, but heavier, carriage, inclosed, except in front, and having a door at each side.","pos":""}],"ROCKER":[{"def":"Same as Rock shaft.","pos":""}],"ROCKERED":[{"def":"Shaped like a rocker; curved; as, a rockered keel.","pos":""}],"ROCKERY":[{"def":"A mound formed of fragments of rock, earth, etc.","pos":""}],"ROCKET":[{"def":"An artificial firework consisting of a cylindrical case of paper or metal filled with a composition of combustible ingredients, as niter, charcoal, and sulphur, and fastened to a guiding stick.","pos":""},{"def":"A blunt lance head used in the joust.","pos":""}],"ROCKETER":[{"def":"A bird, especially a pheasant, which, being flushed, rises straight in the air like a rocket.","pos":""}],"ROCKFISH":[{"def":"Sebastichthys, as the red rockfish (S.","pos":""}],"ROCKINESS":[{"def":"The state or quality of being rocky.","pos":""}],"ROCKING":[{"def":"Having a swaying, rolling, or back-and-forth movement; used for rocking.","pos":""}],"ROCKING-CHAIR":[{"def":"A chair mounted on rockers, in which one may rock.","pos":""}],"ROCKING-HORSE":[{"def":"The figure of a horse, mounted upon rockers, for children to ride.","pos":""}],"ROCKING-STONE":[{"def":"A stone, often of great size and weight, resting upon another stone, and so exactly poised that it can be rocked, or slightly moved, with but little force.","pos":""}],"ROCKLESS":[{"def":"Being without rocks.","pos":""}],"ROCKLING":[{"def":"Any species of small marine fishes of the genera Onos and Rhinonemus (formerly Motella), allied to the cod.","pos":""}],"ROCKROSE":[{"def":"A name given to any species of the genus Helianthemum, low shrubs or herbs with yellow flowers, especially the European H.","pos":""}],"ROCKWEED":[{"def":"Any coarse seaweed growing on sea-washed rocks, especially Fucus.","pos":""}],"ROCKWOOD":[{"def":"Ligniform asbestus; also, fossil wood.","pos":""}],"ROCKWORK":[{"def":"Stonework in which the surface is left broken and rough.","pos":""}],"ROCKY":[{"def":"Full of, or abounding in, rocks; consisting of rocks; as, a rocky mountain; a rocky shore.","pos":""},{"def":"Like a rock; as, the rocky orb of a shield.","pos":""}],"ROCOA":[{"def":"The orange-colored pulp covering the seeds of the tropical plant Bixa Orellana, from which annotto is prepared.","pos":""}],"ROCOCO":[{"def":"A florid style of ornamentation which prevailed in Europe in the latter part of the eighteenth century.","pos":""}]}